    <p><i>Note in these scripts, I generally use lat/lon for lati=C2=ADtude=
/longi=C2=ADtude in degrees, and =CF=86/=CE=BB for
        lati=C2=ADtude/longi=C2=ADtude in radians =E2=80=93 having found th=
at mixing degrees &amp; radians is often the
        easiest route to head-scratching bugs...</i></p>

    <aside><p><i>Historical aside</i>:
        The height of tech=C2=ADnology for navigator=E2=80=99s calculations=
 used to be log tables. As there is no
        (real) log of a negative number, the =E2=80=98versine=E2=80=99 enab=
led them to keep trig func=C2=ADtions in
        positive numbers. Also, the sin=C2=B2(=CE=B8/2) form of the haversi=
ne avoided addition (which en=C2=ADtailed
        an anti-log lookup, the addi=C2=ADtion, and a log lookup).
        Printed <a href=3D"http://haversine.files.wordpress.com/2012/08/hav=
ersines.jpg">tables</a> for the
        haver=C2=ADsine/in=C2=ADverse-haver=C2=ADsine (and its log=C2=ADari=
thm, to aid
        multip=C2=ADlica=C2=ADtions) saved navi=C2=ADgators from squaring s=
ines, com=C2=ADputing square roots,
        etc =E2=80=93 arduous and error-prone activ=C2=ADities.</p>
    </aside>

    <p>The <a href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Haversine_formula">haver=
sine</a>
        formula<sup><a href=3D"http://mathforum.org/library/drmath/view/518=
79.html">1</a></sup> =E2=80=98remains
        particularly well-conditioned for numerical computa=C2=ADtion even =
at small distances=E2=80=99 =E2=80=93 unlike
        calcula=C2=ADtions based on the <span title=3D"cos c =3D cos a cos =
b + sin a sin b cos C"><i>spherical law
        of cosines</i></span>. The =E2=80=98(re)versed sine=E2=80=99 is <sp=
an class=3D"formula">1=E2=88=92cos=CE=B8</span>, and the
        =E2=80=98half-versed-sine=E2=80=99 is <span class=3D"formula">(1=E2=
=88=92cos=CE=B8)/2</span> or <span class=3D"formula">sin=C2=B2(=CE=B8/2)</s=
pan> as used above.
        Once widely used by navigators, it was described by Roger Sinnott i=
n
        <a href=3D"https://skyandtelescope.org/"><i>Sky &amp; Telescope</i>=
</a>
        magazine in 1984 (=E2=80=9CVirtues of the Haversine=E2=80=9D): Sinn=
ott explained that the angular separa=C2=ADtion
        between Mizar and Alcor in Ursa Major =E2=80=93 0=C2=B011=E2=80=B24=
9.69=E2=80=B3 =E2=80=93 could be accurately calculated in <a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/BASIC">Basic</a> on a
        <a href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/TRS-80#modeliii">TRS-80</a>=
 using the haversine.</p>
    <p>For the curious, <i>c</i> is the angular distance in radians, and <i=
>a</i> is the square of half
        the chord length between the points.</p>
    <p>If <code>atan2</code> is not available, <i>c</i> could be calculated
        from <span class=3D"formula">2 =E2=8B=85 asin( min(1, =E2=88=9A<spa=
n class=3D"radicand">a</span>) )</span>
        (including protec=C2=ADtion against rounding errors).</p>
    <p>Using Chrome on an aging Core i5 PC, a distance calcula=C2=ADtion ta=
kes around
        <a href=3D"https://www.movable-type.co.uk/scripts/performance/latlo=
ng-spherical.html">2 =E2=80=93 5 micro=C2=ADseconds</a> (hence around 200,0=
00 =E2=80=93 500,000 per second).
        Little to no benefit is obtained by factoring out common terms; pro=
bably the JIT compiler
        optimises them out.</p>

    <h4 id=3D"cosine-law">Spherical Law of Cosines</h4>

    <p>In fact, JavaScript (and most modern computers &amp; languages) use =
=E2=80=98IEEE 754=E2=80=99 64-bit floating-point
        numbers, which provide 15 significant figures of precision. By my e=
stimate, with this precision,
        the simple <a href=3D"http://mathworld.wolfram.com/SphericalTrigono=
metry.html">spherical law of
        cosines</a> formula (cos <i>c</i> =3D cos <i>a</i> cos <i>b</i> + s=
in <i>a</i> sin <i>b</i> cos <i>C</i>)
        gives well-condi=C2=ADtioned results down to distances as small as =
a few metres on the earth=E2=80=99s surface.
        <span class=3D"note">(<i>Note that the geodetic form of the law of =
cosines is rearranged from the
        canonical one so that the latitude can be used directly, rather tha=
n the
        <a href=3D"http://mathworld.wolfram.com/Colatitude.html">colatitude=
</a></i>).</span></p>
    <p>This makes the simpler law of cosines a reasonable 1-line alternativ=
e to the haversine formula for
        many geodesy purposes (if not for astronomy). The choice may be dri=
ven by programming language, processor,
        coding context, available trig func=C2=ADtions (in different langua=
ges), etc =E2=80=93 and, for very small distances an
        equirectangular approxima=C2=ADtion may be more suitable.</p>

