    <h3 id=3D"bearing">Bearing</h3>

    <p>In general, your current heading will vary as you  follow a great ci=
rcle path (orthodrome); the
        final heading will differ from the initial heading by varying degre=
es according to distance and
        latitude (if you were to go from say 35=C2=B0N,45=C2=B0E (=E2=89=88=
&nbsp;Baghdad) to 35=C2=B0N,135=C2=B0E (=E2=89=88&nbsp;Osaka), you
        would start on a heading of 60=C2=B0 and end up on a heading of 120=
=C2=B0!).</p>
    <p>This formula is for the initial bearing (sometimes referred to as fo=
rward azimuth) which if
        followed in a straight line along a great-circle arc will take you =
from the start point to the
        end point:<sup><a href=3D"http://mathforum.org/library/drmath/view/=
55417.html">1</a></sup></p>
