    <p>Key to calculations of rhumb lines is the <i>inverse Gudermannian fu=
nc=C2=ADtion</i><a href=3D"http://mathworld.wolfram.com/InverseGudermannian=
.html">=C2=B9</a>, which gives the =E2=80=98<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Latitude#Isometric_latitude">isometric latitude</a>=E2=80=99 (=CF=
=88), equivalent to the height on a Mercator projec=C2=ADtion map of a give=
n geodetic latitude =E2=80=93 this can be expessed in various ways:</p>
    <table class=3D"width-full">
        <tbody><tr><td></td><td class=3D"formula">=CF=88 =3D ln( tan(<sup>=
=CF=80</sup>/<sub>4</sub> + <sup>=CF=86</sup>/<sub>2</sub>) )</td></tr>
        <tr><td></td><td class=3D"formula">=CF=88 =3D ln( tan=CF=86 + sec=
=CF=86 ) [i.e. ln( tan=CF=86 + 1/cos=CF=86 )]</td></tr>
        <tr><td></td><td class=3D"formula">=CF=88 =3D asinh( tan=CF=86 ) [=
=E2=89=A1 atanh( sin=CF=86 )]</td></tr>
    </tbody></table>
    <p>The isometric latitude of course tends to infinity at the poles (in =
keeping with the Mercator projec=C2=ADtion).</p>
    <p class=3D"grey"><i>For obsessives, this is a simplification of the fu=
ll ellipsoidal version:</i></p>
    <table class=3D"width-full grey">
        <tbody><tr><td></td><td class=3D"formula"><i>=CF=88 =3D ln( tan(=CF=
=80/4+=CF=86/2) =E2=8B=85 [ (1=E2=88=92e=E2=8B=85sin=CF=86) / (1+e=E2=8B=85=
sin=CF=86)&nbsp;]<sup>e/2</sup>)</i></td></tr>
        <tr><td></td><td class=3D"formula"><i>=CF=88 =3D asinh(tan=CF=86) =
=E2=88=92 e=E2=8B=85atanh(e=E2=8B=85sin=CF=86)</i></td></tr>
    </tbody></table>
    <p class=3D"grey"><i>where </i>e<i> is the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/Eccentricity_(mathematics)#Ellipses" class=3D"grey">eccentrici=
ty</a></i></p>

    <p>The formulas to derive Mercator projection easting and northing coor=
dinates from spherical latitude and longitude are then:</p>
<table class=3D"width-full">
