 =CF=86/2) )</td></tr>
</tbody></table>
<p>The following formulas are from Ed Williams=E2=80=99 aviation formulary<=
a href=3D"http://www.edwilliams.org/avform.htm#Rhumb">=C2=B9</a>.</p>

<h4 id=3D"rhumb-distance">Distance</h4>

<p>Since a rhumb line is a straight line on a Mercator projec=C2=ADtion, th=
e distance between two points
    along a rhumb line is the length of that line (by Pythagoras); but the =
distor=C2=ADtion of the
    projec=C2=ADtion needs to be compensated for.</p>
<p>On a constant latitude course (travelling east-west), this compensa=C2=
=ADtion is simply
    <span class=3D"formula">cos=CF=86</span>; in the general case, it is <s=
pan class=3D"formula">=CE=94=CF=86/=CE=94=CF=88</span>
    where <span class=3D"formula">=CE=94=CF=88 is the =E2=80=98isometric=E2=
=80=99 (projected) latitude difference.</span></p>
