<p id=3D"notes"><i>Notes:</i></p>
<ul class=3D"note">
    <li id=3D"ellipsoid">Accuracy: since the earth is not quite a sphere, t=
here are small errors in
        using spherical geometry; the earth is actually roughly <b>ellipsoi=
dal</b> (or more precisely,
        oblate spheroidal) with a radius varying between about 6,378km (equ=
atorial) and 6,357km (polar),
        and local radius of curvature varying from 6,336km (equatorial meri=
dian) to 6,399km (polar).
        6,371 km is the generally accepted value for the earth=E2=80=99s
        <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Earth_radius#Mean_radius">=
mean radius</a>. This means that errors
        from assuming spherical geometry might be up to 0.55% crossing the =
equator, though generally
        below 0.3%, depending on latitude and direction of travel (<i>whube=
r</i> explores this in excellent
        detail on <a href=3D"http://gis.stackexchange.com/questions/25494#2=
5580">stackexchange</a>).
        An accuracy of better than 3m in 1km is mostly good enough for me, =
but if you want greater
        accuracy, you could use the <a href=3D"https://www.movable-type.co.=
uk/scripts/latlong-vincenty.html">Vincenty</a> formula for
        calculating geodesic distances on ellipsoids, which gives results a=
ccurate to within 1mm.
        (Out of sheer perversity =E2=80=93 I=E2=80=99ve never needed such a=
ccuracy =E2=80=93 I looked up this formula and
        discovered the JavaScript implementation was simpler than I expecte=
d).</li>
    <li>Trig functions take arguments in <b>radians</b>, so latitude, longi=
tude, and bearings in
        <b>degrees</b> (either decimal or degrees/minutes/seconds) need to =
be converted to radians,
        rad =3D deg=E2=8B=85=CF=80/180. When converting radians back to deg=
rees (deg =3D rad=E2=8B=85180/=CF=80), West is negative
        if using signed decimal degrees. For bearings, values in the range =
-=CF=80 to +=CF=80 [-180=C2=B0 to +180=C2=B0]
        need to be converted to 0 to +2=CF=80 [0=C2=B0=E2=80=93360=C2=B0]; =
this can  be done by (brng+360)%360 where % is
        the (floating point) modulo operator (note that different languages=
 implement the
        <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Modulo_operation">modulo o=
peration</a> in different
        ways).</li>
    <li>All bearings are with respect to <b>true north</b>, 0=C2=B0=3DN, 90=
=C2=B0=3DE, etc; if you are working
        from a compass, magnetic north varies from true north in a complex =
way around the earth,
        and the difference has to be compensated for by variances indicated=
 on local maps.</li>
    <li>The <b>atan2</b>() function widely used here takes two arguments, a=
tan2(y, x), and computes
        the arc tangent of the ratio y/x. It is more flexible than atan(y/x=
), since it handles x=3D0,
        and it also returns values in all 4 quadrants -=CF=80 to +=CF=80 (t=
he atan function returns values
        in the range -=CF=80/2 to +=CF=80/2).</li>
    <li>If you implement any formula involving atan2 in a spreadsheet (Micr=
osoft <b>Excel</b>,
        LibreOffice Calc, Google Sheets, Apple Numbers), you will need to r=
everse  the arguments, as
        <a href=3D"http://office.microsoft.com/en-gb/excel/HP052089911033.a=
spx">Excel</a> etc have them
        the opposite way around from <a href=3D"https://developer.mozilla.o=
rg/en/Core_JavaScript_1.5_Reference/Objects/Math/atan2">JavaScript</a>
        =E2=80=93 conventional order is atan2(y, x), but Excel uses atan2(x=
, y). To use atan2 in a (VBA) macro,
        you can use WorksheetFunction.Atan2(). </li>
    <li>If you are using <b>Google Maps</b>, several of these functions are=
 now provided in the Google
        Maps API V3 =E2=80=98spherical=E2=80=99 library (computeDistanceBet=
ween(), computeHeading(), computeOffset(),
        interpolate(), etc; note they use a default Earth radius of 6,378,1=
37 meters).</li>
    <li>If you use UK Ordnance Survey Grid References, I have implemented a=
 script for
        <a href=3D"https://www.movable-type.co.uk/scripts/latlong-os-gridre=
f.html">converting between Lat/Long &amp; OS Grid References</a>.</li>
    <li>If you use UTM coordinates or MGRS grid references, I have implemen=
ted scripts for
        <a href=3D"https://www.movable-type.co.uk/scripts/latlong-utm-mgrs.=
html">converting between Lat/Long, UTM, &amp; MGRS</a>.</li>
    <li>I learned a lot from the US Census Bureau <a href=3D"https://www.mo=
vable-type.co.uk/scripts/gis-faq-5.1.html">GIS FAQ</a> which is no
        longer available, so I=E2=80=99ve made a copy.</li>
    <li>Thanks to Ed Williams=E2=80=99 <a href=3D"http://www.edwilliams.org=
/avform.htm">Aviation Formulary</a>
        for many of the formulas.</li>
    <li>For <b>miles</b>, divide km by 1.609344</li>
    <li>For <b>nautical miles</b>, divide km by 1.852</li>
</ul>

<hr class=3D"fullwidth">

<p id=3D"postscript">See below for the JavaScript source code,
    also available on <a href=3D"https://github.com/chrisveness/geodesy">Gi=
tHub</a>. Full
    <a href=3D"https://www.movable-type.co.uk/scripts/geodesy-library.html"=
>documentation</a> is available, as well as a
    <a href=3D"https://www.movable-type.co.uk/scripts/test/geodesy-test.htm=
l">test suite</a>.</p>
<p>Note I use Greek letters in variables representing maths symbols convent=
ionally presented as Greek letters:
    I value the great benefit in legibility over the minor inconvenience in=
 typing (if you
    encounter any problems, ensure your <code>&lt;head&gt;</code> includes =
<code>&lt;meta charset=3D"utf-8"&gt;</code>),
    and use UTF-8 encoding when saving files).</p>
<p>With its untyped C-style syntax, JavaScript reads remarkably close to ps=
eudo-code: exposing the
    algorithms with a minimum of syntactic distractions. These functions sh=
ould be simple to
    translate into other languages if required, though can also be used as-=
is in browsers and Node.js.</p>
<p>For convenience &amp; clarity, I have extended the base JavaScript <code=
>Number</code> object with
    <code>toRadians()</code> and <code>toDegrees()</code> methods: I don=E2=
=80=99t see great likelihood of
    conflicts, as these are ubiquitous operations.</p>
<p>I also have a page illustrating the use of the spherical law of cosines =
for <a href=3D"https://www.movable-type.co.uk/scripts/latlong-db.html">sele=
cting
    points from a database</a> within a specified bounding circle =E2=80=93=
 the example is based on MySQL+PDO,
    but should be extensible to other DBMS platforms.</p>
<p id=3D"spreadsheets">Several people have asked about example <b>Excel</b>=
 spreadsheets, so I have implemented the
    <a href=3D"https://www.movable-type.co.uk/scripts/latlong-distance+bear=
ing.xls">distance &amp; bearing</a> and the <a href=3D"https://www.movable-=
type.co.uk/scripts/latlong-dest-point.xls">destination
    point</a> formulas as spreadsheets, in a form which breaks down the all=
 stages involved to illustrate
    the operation.</p>
<p><i>February 2019</i>: I have refactored the library to use ES modules, a=
s well as extending it in
    scope; see the <a href=3D"https://github.com/chrisveness/geodesy">GitHu=
b</a> README and CHANGELOG for details.</p>
<p>Performance: as noted above, the haversine distance calculation takes ar=
ound
    <a href=3D"https://www.movable-type.co.uk/scripts/performance/latlong-s=
pherical.html">2 =E2=80=93 5 micro=C2=ADseconds</a> (hence around 200,000 =
=E2=80=93
    500,000 per second). I have yet to complete timing tests on other calcu=
lations.</p>
<p id=3D"other-languages"><b>Other languages</b>: I cannot support translat=
ions into other languages, but if you have ported
    the code to another language, I am happy to provide links here.</p>
<ul>
    <li>Brian Lambert has made an <a href=3D"https://github.com/softwarener=
d/GreatCircle">Objective-C</a> version.</li>
    <li>Jean Brouwers has made a <a href=3D"https://github.com/mrJean1/PyGe=
odesy">Python</a> version.</li>
    <li>Vahan Aghajanyan has made a <a href=3D"https://github.com/vahancho/=
erkir">C++</a> version.</li>
    <li>Bahad=C4=B1r Arslan has made a <a href=3D"https://github.com/bahadi=
rarslan/Jeodezi">Kotlin</a> version and a <a href=3D"https://github.com/bah=
adirarslan/jeodezi_dart">Dart</a> version.</li>
</ul>
